With the possible exception of people who grew up with classical and take it for granted, the pleasure of discovering how satisfying 'music as music' can be is something you can't put back in the box once it's out. It's not really possible to listen to most popular music in the same way afterwards.

Some people do flaunt an interest in classical music as a social identity, but not really in the same way as popular music subcultures. Generally, it manifests as snobbishness and superficiality, people who attach themselves to classical music because of its perceived social value or edifying qualities without much knowledge or interest in the music itself (and although you might think so, this is not limited to politically conservative listeners by any means). Beyond that, culture war stuff is inevitable nowadays, although I don't think classical gets the worst of it aside from a predictable flare up every now and again about white supremacist music theory or fuming about dead white men in the canon.

>>114556032
>Though I also think that the theatrical/drama element plays a major role in the singing style of opera too.
True. Expression is just as important as beautiful singing in opera. Opera also developed parallell with the development of singing. The first time a tenor ever sang a full high C with 'chest' was in 1831. All music before that tenors had sung high Cs in a more falsetto-like voice. Opera has always had an element of bravura and virtuosity. But it gradually went from singing fast and high notes to all the more singing powerful and high notes, which suits the expressive, dramatic nature of the art form very well.

In a second the guests had comprehended that I intended to avenge Mendelssohn’s butchering of my poor Rhapsodic, although I suppose many thought it a rather hazardous attempt to play a difficult composition in a new garb or arrangement on the spur of the moment, especially with the composer sitting within two yards of the keyboard. However, I did what I had announced to do, and at the conclusion, Mendelssohn, instead of bursting out with indignation and rage at my impudence and liberty, took my right hand in his, and turned it over, backward and forward, and bent the fingers this way and that, finally remarking laughingly that since I had beaten him on the keyboard, the only way of vindication was to challenge me to a boxing match. However, since he had now examined my hand, he would have to abandon that particular course of action. So everything passed over smoothly, and what might have been a very unpleasant meeting turned out a most enjoyable evening.”

posts.com: sometimes you can have unwanted/unnecessary low end stuff that builds up and when you are compressing and limiting your mix in different ways, the low end is hitting it hard and causing it to attenuate way to much without making it "audibly" louder. so even on unsuspecting tracks ill always have a hard pass around 80-150hz . also having some compressors on return tracks with an EQ before them so the low end isnt hitting them as hard, can help increase the volume heaps. driving 2 or 3 limiters on the master bus without pushing them too hard to get your desired level is a good way to dial it in.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114568046
Be careful when highpassing return tracks/sends that don't have reverbs or delays on them, as you might introduce phasing issues when applying this technique incorrectly. That's a whole different swamp to get out of. But in general you are correct: there could be too much low end information triggering the compressor/limiter. TDR Nova is an excellent free compressor with an internal sidechain so you can attenuate the compressor being triggered by the low end, no need to set up a HP beforehand. It is still a wide-band compressor, meaning it will compress the entire spectrum of the track on your mixer channel.
Also learn how to apply saturation, it shaves off the transients, giving you more headroom, while making the average volume of the track louder. Soft and hard clipping are also great tools when applied correctly.

>>114569075
Also, since I'm an autist who can't shut up about this stuff, I can't stress enough how a little often goes a long way, since it's very easy to go overboard with these techniques. Also, contrary to all the bs mixing "advice" on the internet: don't high pass all your tracks to shit. Your mix will sound harsh and lifeless. Don't do anything if it's not needed and don't do anything by default.
Also, when you have a good arrangement, mixing becomes so much easier. I would say that roughly 80% of the mix is established in the arrangement. A bad arrangement will often not lead to a good mix and you end up fixing rather than mixing which only leads to frustration. Good luck and enjoy the process.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Pay attention to transient peaks usually from kick and snare, get them under control (eq or sat or both), boom. Instant headroom unless you're fucking up with elsewhere (too much low end etc).

It's depressing how many years I wasted complicating things, but in the end paying attention to what my kick and snare were doing fixed my volume problems pretty much instantly. Don't even think about it now.

Oh yeah another thing, I hope you've been testing all your mixes in mono. If not, say goodbye to everything you've made and a whole lot of effort. Mid/side EQ is your friend, and I wish I'd known about that a lot sooner.

It's not. You can find it on the Magma web press book, it´s from an interview with Extra No. 1, December 1970.
http://robert.guillerault.free.fr/magma/textes/1970/extra01.htm
All interviews: http://robert.guillerault.free.fr/magma/index2.htm

>connecting Goebbels, one of the most quotable Nazis of all time, to that phrase
The problem is that a German original translated to French translated to English.

"L´armee de ceux qui sont tombeés n´a pas rendu les armes,elle marche das le rang des soldats"

this could be roughly translated as
"the army of those who have fallen, has not put down (or back) its weapons, it marches within the ranks of our soldiers"

Initially, this sentence and its symbolism is rooted in the so called Horst Wessel Lied, the unofficial Nazi Germany hymn...Horst Wessel was shot by communists in 1930, and it was notably Joseph Goebbels who made him the ulimate martyr for Nazi Germany, and JG was also responsible for a wide distribution of the Horst Wessel Lied. For anyone interested in Germany it is very well known that the Horst Wessel Lied and main symbolisms used by Goebbels are tighly linked with each other.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114563849
The loudness you get depends on how much bandwith each element in your mix uses. In the case of your example, its a extremely barebones track with really nothing in the mids and highs so sonny can just smash that shit into a clipper really hard without it starting to pump or distort.

You would not get this sort of loudness with a very lush and rich sounding track without it sounding distorted in parts or without lowend or highend ducking.

In your case, you should start lowcutting and highcutting instruments. Like sub bass that doesnt need alot of top end and leads and instruments that doesnt need low end.

Also learn to use a clipper.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114563849
use two limiters. It'll let you get more volume while staying fairly transparent, compared to if you tried getting that same volume with one limiter

You can cut out everything below 50hz and everything above 15khz and just scoop the mids by 7-8 db and smash it into a clipper and it will probably be the loudest shit around, but it will sound trash on anything but a smartphone/laptop speaker.

>>114563849
Listen here, I'll tell you how to compete in the loudness war. Go to each individual sound in your track and analyse it with an oscilloscope. If you see peaks in the waveform get rid of them with a clipper or limiter, but listen carefully to not overdo it. As soon as the sound changes back off, we don't want to change the sound only get rid of those little peaks. Do this also on your bus channels and on the master channel, before the compressors in the signal chain. You probably have to bounce those tracks due to the amount of clippers/limiters needed to give your CPU some relief. If you bounce those tracks remember to use the highest oversampling option.

If done correctly you'll have so much more headroom on the master channel with almost no audible difference in sound, your compressors will work more smoothly without those peaks and with your last limiter you'd be able to push hard for loudness. See pic and compare the numbers in the red boxes.

I was wondering the following, which, perhaps someone here can provide an answer.

Let's say an album has 9 songs (all the same genre, style, feel, etc.). In order for them to sound consistent and similar to one another, is it customary to mix one track and use that as the sort of "template" when mixing the rest? For example, saving EQ, reveb, etc. settings for a crash cymbal in one song and then just simply applying those same settings to the crash cymbal in the next song? And the same for snare, etc.? And then of course, could that same principle be applied to guitars, vocals, etc. etc. etc.?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114568120
pls /prod/, I'm this close to releasing

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114568171
No, each song should be mixed individually. Sound choice is probably more important than mixing. So you are making a conscious decision in the production to create a consistent and cohesive sound for an album. You limit yourself in terms of drum kits, drum machine, instruments, synths, mic...
You can of course copy some mixing tools for example using the same room reverb so it sounds like all tracks were recorded in the same room. Or using the same plugins with their specific characters like compressors, color EQ, saturation and so on. But the mixing process itself should be individual, don't limit yourself to a "template" of another song.

Mastering is something else. Here you are doing subtle changes and it is common to A/B test and use other songs of the album as a reference to create the final touches for a cohesive sound.

first step, chain mastering.
For each master channel and its bus use some sort of soft compresion, not too much it will add up later. Or call it chain compresion.

second step: or step 1.5
>>114563915
>start lowcutting and highcutting instruments
this is very important, drums and bass always fight with each other, at least the kick and bass.

step 2:
keep enough headroom in your production, watch for spikes they might fuck you up later in the mastering proces. You can do a little mastering during the production process but keep these two stages seperated.
Consolodate the final track and start to master on the clean wave file. If done right there should be no spikes fucking you up and a lot of headroom to fill it.

>>114559673
Depends on the type of shredding. For example, I like to compare Yngwie and Uli Jon Roth. Yngwie relies on flash to trick the listener into thinking it's impressive, though the active listener will notice how it's often directionless, and seldom on tempo, and usually has nothing to do with what notes the other instruments are playing. His style is "playing fast over common classical chord progressions", and that's about as deep as it goes.
On the other hand, Uli (who was a major inspiration for Yngwie) always plays with the rest of the band in mind, knows what notes to emphasize to go with the chord progression, knows how to switch between fast runs and slower melodies to break up the pacing, knows how to tie the fast runs and melodic riffs together so they flow with direction, stays on tempo, and most glaringly, is a good rhythm player.
Though neither of them are very innovative in their musical writing, the latter is much more enjoyable to listen to for extended periods than the former. It all comes down to musicianship, not just guitar playing.

posts.com:
As much as grunge is over-saturated on this board to some extent, for many I feel it was real turning point for their taste in music, and that's why they like it.

For me, it was Alice in Chains, and of all things, their self-titled album. Yup, the one that sounded nothing like the others, was poorly produced, and was last record before Layne died.
That was the album that got me into sludge metal. I've actually mentioned this on this board before, so yeah, I'm the same anon, but I'm bringing it up again to see if anyone has a similar story.
Or your own story.
What was the band for you?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I heard paradise lost gothic in a shed at night lit by candles with the other boys that I used to walk across moors at night drinking cider with. That guitar sound made so much sense to me that it was death metal all the way. Deicide, at the gates, carcass, EntombeD, Slayer south of heaven especially.

By then I'd already heard VU, Hendrix, ZZ Top, pink floyd, roxy Music, van Morrison, the who. I knew trout mask and decals. When I heard gothic I thought, 'that's it that's where we are, walking around on this morbid earth in the freezing cold' .

Kinda cringe but it was Bullet for My Valentine, with their Scream Aim Fire album. It's still a good piece of metalcore/thrash, all the other B4MV are trash. I was lucky in a way, but what attracted me were the hardest parts of the music.
From then on I listened to Metallica, then I became a huge Gojira fan, then got into Napalm Death.
It wasn't until highschool that I started listening to doom and stoner. When I discovered Electric Wizard and weed, my whole world shattered. I was reborn.
I didn't listen to black metal until I was 21. I'll turn 27 in two weeks, I listen to a lot of stuff now, far from only metal. I'll try to make a career in entertainment, I'm trying to become a stage manager. Music is my life, it has been a big part of my family for generations.

>>114558813
Glad he's back to his roots ig, being a loser provocateur. While he's done some great stuff in studio nothing compares to the home recorded stuff
Really the greatest pop songwriter of a generation (and if you disagree, pay attention to the metre of his songs, esp weird ones like "Strange Fires", how melody dictates structure often and how volatile and full of turns the structure is, the layering and the fact he made the vast majority of them by himself over like 5 years) and kind of like Lil B, RXK Nephew in a lot of ways people don't appreciate: he just brute forced his way to the top, rerecording until it sounded right. He literally spent years just recording until he figures out. Plus the fact that a lot of his songs are fully composed in his head is a lot closer to more classical composers than a lot of people appreciate. I do say that you've probably got to get into him at ages 14-20 because he's nothing radical but his whole attitude really appeals to dejected young men (ie me). He said that his ethos while recording Scared Famous was to actively write songs that were at exact odds with his lack of a life -- ironically, I think at times it can be very revealing to the composer underneath.
And I mean he's not a good person but you could tell that from his music

I would roughly describe iconic works as possessing the following qualities:

>capturing a cultural zeitgeist
>creating (or at least successfully embodying) a particular archetype
>influence - the work has had an observable, significant impact on culture/art
>recognizable - the work possesses qualities that are immediately distinctive

>>114563119
I don't listen to pop punk either. Although MCR admittedly has some similarities with pop punk bands (mostly in terms of arrangements and production), I think "pop punk" is way too reductionist of a label to stick on them. Pop punk bands were chugging away on three chords and whining nasally about mom and dad. MCR was a lot more ambitious, lyrical, and thoughtful than those bands. Their music is full of engaging musical ideas (dynamics, counterpoint, dissonance, harmonies) and lyrics were much more artful - cinematic, humorous, subversive, romantic.

If you're willing to listen, here are some tracks that are clearly more than just pop punk:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GaLaMd_EAo4

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RSAoJJzVXYY

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V2kWUJkRvVs

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NxQVElXpTVg

If you just don't like them, that's fair, but I do find it tedious how people dismiss them and mischaracterize their sound, usually because they (justifiably) find the fanbase cringe. "I'm Not Okay" isn't everything they've done.

for me it went like this
>acquire ableton

>supplement any further niche questions about plugins, production techniques etc with other channels (YSAP, produce like a pro)
took a week or so to get very comfortable with everything but it’s second nature now.

>He mixes for guitar. It's not an improvement, unless you mainly want to hear guitar.
Well unless you are just doing a raw tape transfer with no mastering you'd need some sort of reference point, no?
I compared a few different masters side-by-side, and while he certainly pulls the guitar out of the song so-to-speak, he does that will all the instruments he can isolate. I don't think he's that guilty of making the guitar(s) stand out egregiously. Listening to Close to the Edge side-by-side for example, the greatest emphasis was added to the vocals, which depending on how you like those balanced is either a gain or a loss. With that being said, he definitely sterilizes and sharpens the sound in a way that doesn't work well every time, and depending on your setup you might not appreciate the added gain (though it doesn't clip or compress).

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114496636
These are their albums worth checking out

>Killing Technology
Proggy thrash metal
>Dimension Hatross
Thrashy prog metal, less emphasis on the thrash. Probably their proggiest album.
>Nothingface
Progressive metal with a pretty unique post-punk edge, not so much thrash metal
>The Outer Limits
Pretty solid prog metal with a clear early 90s alternative rock sound. Jack Luminous is their best song.
>The Wake
Surprisingly great return to form to their Dimension Hatross sound after 25 years of mediocrity

Their first two albums aren't prog.
Angel Rat's a weird alternative rock/metal album, some people like it but it's not prog.
Negatron is their obligatory 1990s 80s-thrash-metal-band-gone-butt-metal album but with Voivod's signature angular dissonant riffing style.
Phobos is Negatron but more spaced out and proggy, might be worth listening to if you don't mind 90s butt metal.

Literally everything Voivod's put out in the 2000s and early 2010s has been unremarkable until The Wake.
